# 5. Demonstration I: f49v — PROCESS/operator key

## 5.1 Regime

PROCESS / operator demonstration.

## 5.2 Why this folio was selected

f49v is selected because it appears to expose the closure grammar directly. It contains a numbered 1–5 structure corresponding to five y-closed vertical operator chains. The value of y as closure was derived before f49v was interpreted in this way; f49v therefore functions as a confirmation environment rather than the origin of the rule.

## 5.3 Vertical operator chains

```text
1. f  -> o -> r -> y
2. ch -> o -> k -> s -> p -> o -> r -> y
3. e  -> o -> s -> p -> o -> r -> y
4. ch -> o -> d -> y
5. ch -> k -> y
```

## 5.4 Structural-functional translation

```text
1. variant/preparation -> field -> output/relation -> closure
2. active frame -> field -> stabilize -> regulate -> procedure-init -> field -> output/relation -> closure
3. grade/intensity -> field -> regulate -> procedure-init -> field -> output/relation -> closure
4. active frame -> field -> transform/process -> closure
5. active frame -> stabilize/fix -> closure
```

## 5.5 Plain functional rendering

The page demonstrates five completed process chains. Each chain presents a short operator path and terminates in y, the closure/finalization operator. The first chain moves from preparatory/variant initiation through field and output to closure. The second and third chains demonstrate regulated field-output procedures. The fourth chain demonstrates active transformation to closure. The fifth chain demonstrates active stabilization to closure.

## 5.6 Demonstration value

This page shows that y is not merely a frequent final sign. It functions as the explicit closure of completed operator chains. The numbered structure strengthens the reading because the page appears to expose five closure-delimited demonstrations in a visible sequence.

