# 9. Demonstration V: final compressed star/text folio — BALNEO reading key and visual fractionation

## 9.1 Regime

Final text-heavy / star-labelled compressed notation.

## 9.2 Why this folio type is needed

A page from the final part of the manuscript is essential because these pages appear to represent the most compressed form of the system. Compared with the heavily visual sections, the final pages use mostly text with minimal star or small diagrammatic markers.

Under the present model, this is not a different script. It is the same notation in a more compressed state:

```text
maximum structural encoding
minimal visual support
small star/index marker as classifier or process label
```

## 9.3 Working interpretation

The final text/star pages may function as advanced or summary-level procedural entries. They would make sense only after the reader has learned the operator inventory, regime conventions, and key-page logic elsewhere in the manuscript.

In this view, the final section may be the closest thing to pure recipe text: compact procedural records with minimal visual scaffolding.

## 9.4 Translation format

The selected final folio should be translated continuously, with emphasis on whether the parser can sustain semantic coherence without relying heavily on images.

```text
Original line:
[Voynich tokens]

Structural-functional reading:
[token-by-token reading]

Plain procedural rendering:
[continuous recipe/procedure rendering]
```

## 9.5 Demonstration value

This is the strongest test of practical readability. If the parser can read a final text-heavy page coherently, it shows that the model is not dependent on rich illustrations. It also supports the hypothesis that the manuscript is a training and application guide for a compact internal recipe notation.

